# 1) Clean the scalar 'director' column with pure GPU string ops
#    remove spaces, lowercase, fill nulls with empty string
#    (regex=False makes replace a literal op)
df2['director'] = (
    df2['director']
      .str.replace(' ', '', regex=False)
      .str.lower()
      .fillna('')
)

# 2) Clean the list-of-strings columns via join→vectorized replace/lower→split
#    this avoids expensive explode/groupby and keeps everything on the GPU
for feature in ['cast', 'keywords', 'genres']:
    # join each list into a single '|'–delimited string
    joined = df2[feature].str.join('|')
    # remove spaces and lowercase in one go
    cleaned = (
        joined
          .str.replace(' ', '', regex=False)
          .str.lower()
    )
    # split back into lists
    split = cleaned.str.split('|')
    # rows where the original list was empty become an empty string → ['']
    # mask those back to [] so we exactly match the original empty‐list behavior
    df2[feature] = split.mask(joined == '', [])
Reason: By converting each list column into a delimited string, we leverage cudf’s fully‐vectorized .str.replace and .str.lower on the GPU, then split back into lists. This eliminates the costly explode→groupby path (and the out‐of‐memory error), keeps all data on the GPU, and remains semantically equivalent even for empty lists.
